Treb 8/7/2024 8:54 PM
That makes perfect sense to me. I think a common concept in caring professions is to try and sort of, take yourself out of what you are doing to prevent harm to yourself. There’s a term in counseling called countertransference, wherein a person’s life or what they are describing resonates with them on a personal level. It’s something that those folks have to work with a lot, because well, we’re human and it’s odd not to feel that from time to time. And when you do feel that the usual course of action is to talk it out with a supervisor to make those feelings known to somebody and to explore that. I don’t know what you’re thinking there but it becomes something different when it’s not just a pet you’re working on, but somebody’s pet, and that’s the hard personal bit that seems like it makes it tough. I’m glad you’re talking to people about it though, that’s definitely the best thing you can do is to make what you’re going through known to somebody.
